{An instructive moment from the tournament winner's memorabilia: how should
White continue?} 23. Bg5 $1 {Exchanging the right pieces in the right moment
is an art. This move order looks stronger to me than} (23. Bd2 {first} Rc7 {
followed by} 24. Bg5 {White is having the advantage here as well but the game
continuation seems more precise.}) 23... Bc5 ({If} 23... Bxg5 24. Qxg5 Qc7 25.
Bf1 Bxc2 {What else?} (25... Rc8 26. Rb2 Rxa3 27. Rcb1 Qd8 28. Qf4 $16) 26.
Nxd4 Ba4 27. Re1 $16 {White's position is harmonious with good control in the
center and better play on the dark squares. Black will run out of useful moves
soon.}) 24. Bd2 $1 {This is why I believe the move order played by the
Hungarian GM is more accurate.} Rxa3 25. Rxa3 Bxa3 26. Ra1 Qc5 (26... Qb2 27.
Qxd4 $16) 27. Nxd4 Bxc2 28. Nxe6 {The positional play is now followed by
tactical blows.} fxe6 29. Qxe6+ Kh8 30. Qxd7 Qxf2+ 31. Kh1 $18 {The winner had
no troubles to convert this massive advantage.} 1-0

