{A bit of help from the opponents is always helpful in the race for the first
place. Here White has a very comfortable advantage and the question is whether
he can make progress?} 25. Nf2 ({Perhaps} 25. a4 $5 $16 {gaining more space on
the queenside and limiting the black knight, would have posed Black more
practical problems.}) 25... Nb5 26. Ne4 {choices, choices...} (26. Kd3 $5 {
looks great since} gxf4 {runs into} 27. c4 Nd6 28. Ne4 $16 {Black's structure
doesn't look healthy at all.}) 26... f5 27. Nxg5 Nxc3 {White lost the thread.}
28. a4 Nd5+ 29. Kf3 a5 ({If} 29... h6 30. Nh3 Nb4 31. Ke2 $1 {It always amazes
me how critical every move is in the endgame.} (31. Ke3 Nc2+ 32. Kd3 Ne1+ $17 {
is losing a pawn by force, with a worse version than the main line.}) 31... Nc2
32. d5 cxd5 33. Kd2 Nd4 34. b4 {may still hold.}) 30. Nh3 Nb4 31. Ke3 Nc2+ 32.
Kd3 Ne1+ 33. Kc4 {White's counterplay on the queenside is too slow. Instead,} (
33. Ke2 $1 {Saves the house from fire.} Nxg2 34. Kf2 Nh4 35. Kg3 Kh5 36. Ng5
$11) 33... Nxg2 34. Kc5 Kh5 35. Kb6 Kg4 36. Ng1 Nxf4 37. Kxa5 (37. Kxb7 {
doesn't help either} Ne6 38. Kxc6 Nxd4+ $19) 37... Nd5 38. b4 f4 39. h3+ Kg3
40. Ne2+ Kf3 {I doubt anyone has ever won a tournament without assistance from
the opposition.} 0-1

