{This game had been a bit of a roller-coaster-ride for both sides. But here
Black evaluated the position correctly and found a brilliant plan. Which one?} 
22... h4 {The right direction,} 23. g4 Nxg4 $1 {backed up with a sound
positional sacrifice.} 24. hxg4 Qxg4 25. f3 Qg5 26. Kh1 d4 {Black's
coordination is eye candy.} 27. exd4 h3 28. Bxh3 Qg3 {It is very difficult to
juggle with the materially unbalanced positions, where every move is like
stepping on a mine field. The slightest innacuracy can be the end of an
otherwise beautifully constructed attack.} ({Instead,} 28... Rc6 $1 {another
piece is brought into the fight.} 29. Ne4 (29. Nf1 Rg6 30. Bg2 Qh5+ 31. Kg1
Bxf3 32. Rd2 cxd4 33. Qd3 Bh4 $1 $19 {White is completely tied up.}) 29... Qh5
30. Qg2 Rg6 $19) 29. Bg2 Rc6 {doesn't work as well as the line seen above
since White can now built up a defense.} 30. Nf1 Qh4+ 31. Kg1 Rg6 32. Qf2 ({
Also} 32. d5 $5 {looks interesting} Rxd5 33. Rxd5 Bxd5 34. Qf2 $13) 32... Qh3 {
Quite often, an error never comes alone. It is White on the winning side now.}
(32... Qxf2+ $5 {Would have kept Black in the game and, perhaps, even more
than that.} 33. Kxf2 Bh4+ 34. Kg1 Bxf3 35. Rd2 Bg5 $36) 33. Nh2 Bd6 34. Ng4
Rxg4 35. fxg4 Qh2+ 36. Kf1 Bg3 37. Qe2 Qh6 38. Bxa8 Rxa8 {I remember we were
watching the game at the dinner table and when White played the next move, we
could not believe it. The Russian GM had 40 minutes on the clock, his opponent
had seconds, it was +... (high number for White) and a resignation was
expected soon. But not after:} 39. dxc5 $4 {The transmission must be wrong.} (
39. Qf3 $18) 39... Qh1# {It was not. Shaking our heads in disbelief, it is
hard to imagine what goes through a chess player's soul and mind in such
moments.} 0-1

